#### Ho-4: Knowing Your Rights as a Renter or Homeowner
*Strategy:* Assert + Decode
*See also:* L-1: Negotiating a Contract (for reading your lease or mortgage), C-7: Understanding Your Rights Where You Live (for rights that vary by jurisdiction), C-4: Advocating for Change (for changing the rules)
*My Man Jeeves:* _Housing law, one might observe, is the domain in which the greatest sums change hands with the least comprehension on one side of the transaction. The landlord retains a property management company that has filed the same lease in the same county for fifteen years. The HOA board has engaged an attorney on retainer who drafted the CC&Rs. The mortgage servicer employs a compliance department that knows precisely which fees are legal and which are merely customary. The individual on the other side of the table has the document they were given and a vague apprehension that some of it is not quite right. That apprehension is, in the general course of things, well founded. The law is specific, it varies by jurisdiction, and it almost invariably provides more rights than one supposes. The difficulty has never been the law itself. The difficulty is that nobody has explained it._
*The Spec:*
::: prompt
I have a question about my rights as a [renter / homeowner / HOA member].
My situation:
— Where I live: [city, state]
— My housing type: [apartment / house / condo / mobile home / HOA community]
— The issue: [describe — lease dispute, security deposit, HOA rule,
   property tax assessment, landlord not making repairs, noise complaint,
   accessibility need, pet restriction, utility billing, or "I just want
   to understand what rights I have"]
— What has happened so far: [if anything — notices sent, conversations
   had, complaints filed]
Please help me:
1. What are my specific rights in this situation under my
   state and local law?
2. What is the process for enforcing those rights — who do I
   contact, what do I file, what are the deadlines?
3. What are the most common mistakes people make in this
   situation that weaken their position?
4. If this involves a dispute: what is my strongest argument,
   and what documentation do I need?
Give me the most conservative, legally accurate answer.
I will verify with a tenant rights organization or attorney.
:::
*What to do with the Output:* Document everything in writing. If your landlord or HOA is violating your rights, your Agent can help you draft the letter — but send it by email or certified mail so there is a record. Many cities have free tenant rights hotlines and legal aid organizations; ask your Agent to find the one in your jurisdiction. The clock on most housing disputes starts running whether you know about the deadline or not.

::: tip
_"I just signed a lease I didn't fully understand. [Paste the section you're worried about.] What did I actually agree to, and is any of it unenforceable in [state]?"_ — The time to understand your lease is now, not when there is a dispute.
:::


::: fairness
Housing rights enforcement varies dramatically by race, income, and geography. Eviction filings are disproportionately concentrated in Black and Latino neighborhoods, even after controlling for income (Desmond, 2016). If your Agent's advice assumes a responsive landlord or a functional enforcement system, say so: _"My landlord ignores repair requests and I'm worried about retaliation if I push harder. What are my protections?"_
:::


::: also
Paste or upload your lease, HOA rules, or property tax assessment directly — file upload works in Claude, Gemini, ChatGPT, and Copilot. See [Appendix G](06-appendix-g-feature-table.xhtml).
:::


